There's no existing single-select with Comparer test. Let me look at the issue more carefully. Let me look at the `NullableObject` dictionary key issue - this is at the core of the problem.

The `_shadowLookup` and `_valueLookup` dictionaries use `NullableObject<T?>` as keys. The `NullableObject<T?>` struct always uses `EqualityComparer<T?>.Default` for equality and hash code. When there's a custom `Comparer` on `MudSelect<T>`, items are registered with the lookup dictionaries but lookups use default equality.

However, on second thought, this issue should affect ALL cases with a custom Comparer - not just initial SelectedValues. But the issue says `MultiSelectWithCustomComparerTest` passes. Let me look at the multi-select test again. In that test, they set comparison after clicking a button. Let me look at it more carefully.

Wait, actually the multi-select test uses `_context.RegisterItem(this)` which stores items in `_valueLookup`. For multi-select, there's no check against `_shadowLookup` for the selected value. The selected text is constructed from `_selectedValues.Select(ConvertSet)` - it doesn't use the item's render fragment.

Let me now look much more carefully at the single-select flow. In the razor template, line 55-58:
```
@if (CanRenderValue)
{
    @GetSelectedValuePresenter()
}
```

`GetSelectedValuePresenter()` at line 258:
```csharp
protected RenderFragment? GetSelectedValuePresenter()
{
    if (!_context.TryGetShadowItemByValue(ReadValue, out var item))
    {
        return null;
    }
    return item.ChildContent;
}
```

But `CanRenderValue` also checks `TryGetShadowItemByValue`:
```csharp
if (!_context.TryGetShadowItemByValue(ReadValue, out var item))
    return false;
```

So `CanRenderValue` returns false when there's no shadow item. When `CanRenderValue` is false, the input type is `InputType.Text` and `ReadText` is displayed.

So the issue is NOT about `CanRenderValue` or display of child content. The issue must be about `ReadText` not being properly populated.

Hmm, wait - let me look at this from a different angle. Let me look at the git log for recent changes to the MudSelect or related Comparer code.

